{We have chosen an old game, simply because we think that the way Black played
in this game is the way we should also play.} 1. c4 Nf6 2. Nc3 e6 3. e4 d5 4.
e5 d4 5. exf6 dxc3 6. fxg7 {This move is very unambitious, as it gives Black
equal chances quite easily.} cxd2+ 7. Bxd2 {White first take on g7 - showing
lack of ambition - and now he takes on d2 with the bishop instead of the queen,
showing that he wants to fight for an opening advantage! According to me, the
White player is confused! But leaving aside all these prejudices, this
position is quite complicated and interesting because of an asymmetrical pawn
structure. One of Black's main advantages is that he has an extra central pawn,
the 'e' pawn, which gives him additional central control.} Bxg7 8. Qc2 {
Defending the b2 pawn.} Nc6 9. Nf3 Qe7 (9... Bd7 {Is also possible, followed
by Qe7 and 0-0-0.}) 10. Bd3 Bd7 (10... Nb4 {Is still not possible because of...
} 11. Qa4+) 11. a3 {Stopping Nb4.} O-O-O 12. Be3 $1 {This move is made to stop
Nd4. White figures out that Black is a little low on space, so he wants to
avoid exchanges. And, true enough, if Black could play Nd4 followed by Bc6, he
could be better.} (12. O-O-O Nd4 $1 {Easing off the space issue with a few
exchanges.} 13. Nxd4 Bxd4 14. Bc3 (14. Bxh7 f5 $19) 14... Bc6 $15) (12. Bxh7 {
Taking this pawn is never an option due to...} f5 $19) (12. O-O Nd4 13. Nxd4
Bxd4 $15 {And again, the open 'g' file, combined with the bishop coming to c6,
gives Black a nice position.}) 12... Kb8 (12... f5 {Black could have directly
started with this move. The idea now is to play Rhf8 followed by e5. I think
currently it was more important to grab the space in the centre rather than
put the king into safety. However, the Kb8 move doesn't hurt Black.} 13. O-O-O
Rhf8 14. Bg5 Bf6 15. Bh6 {Was better.} (15. Bxf6 $6 Qxf6 $15 {Now e5 cannot be
stopped and Black is better.}) 15... Rg8 16. g3 Be8 $1 $15 {Transferring the
bishop to a better diagonal.}) 13. O-O-O f5 $1 {Black plays in the spirit of
his pawn structure, trying to grab more and more space in the centre.} 14. Rhe1
Rhf8 $1 {Defending the f5 pawn, so as to make e5 possible.} 15. Bg5 {The most
natural move.} (15. Kb1 {The main idea of this move is to avoid a check from
g5 later on, when the tactical variations emerge down the 'e' file.} e5 16. Bg5
(16. Nxe5 $5 Qxe5 (16... Nxe5 17. f4 $1) 17. Bxa7+ Kxa7 18. Rxe5 Bxe5 $17 {
Black has a lot of material for the queen.}) 16... Bf6 17. Bxf5 $1 {Now you
can see the advantage of the move Kb1.} (17. Bxf6 Qxf6 $17) 17... Bxg5 (17...
Bxf5 18. Qxf5 Rxd1+ 19. Rxd1 Bxg5 20. Qxg5 Qxg5 21. Nxg5 Rxf2 22. Nxh7 Rxg2 $11
) 18. Bxd7 Rxd7 19. Rxd7 Qxd7 20. Nxg5 Qg4 21. Nf3 Qxg2 $11) 15... Bf6 16. Bxf6
Qxf6 {Now the entire battle will revolve around the fact whether Black can get
to e5 or not. Because if Black can play e5, he will have very strong central
control; and if he can't, then the pawns on f5 and e6 will remain weak. Taking
these factors into consideration, White wasn't on top of his game and played a
normal move which would have given Black the advantage.} 17. Qe2 $6 (17. Qc3 $1
{Only this brilliant move allows White to keep the position equal.} Qxc3+ 18.
bxc3 $13 {Though White has ruined his pawn structure, now executing e5 will be
difficult and Black will be able to blockade the pawns. That means the e6 pawn
will be weak and the bishop on d7 would not be such a strong piece. Hence this
position is dynamically balanced: White's bad pawn structure v Black's not so
good bishop.}) 17... e5 $2 {There was no need to give up the pawn: Black could
have just played Rfe8. Maybe he was afraid that his pawns would be blockaded.}
(17... Rfe8 $1 18. Ne5 Nd4 $1 {The threat now is Ba4, trapping the d1 rook as
Rd2 would fail to Nb3.} 19. Nxd7+ Rxd7 20. Qe5 Qg5+ 21. Kb1 Qxg2 22. Bxf5 Qxf2
23. Bxh7 Nf3 24. Qc3 Rxh7 25. Rf1 Qe2 26. Qxf3 Qxc4 $17 {A long variation; but
it was just to prove the point that Black is better in the ensuing positions.})
18. Nxe5 Nxe5 19. Qxe5 Qg5+ 20. Kb1 Ba4 21. Bc2 Bxc2+ 22. Kxc2 Rxd1 23. Rxd1
Qxg2 {The position is still even. But Black lost in a very instructive pawn
endgame.} 24. Qxf5 Qxf2+ (24... Qg8 $1 {Would have been better.}) 25. Qxf2
Rxf2+ 26. Rd2 Rxd2+ 27. Kxd2 $18 {White is winning this endgame because of his
active king.} Kc8 28. Ke3 Kd7 29. Kf4 Ke6 30. Kg5 Kf7 31. Kh6 Kg8 32. b4 Kh8
33. a4 a6 (33... Kg8 34. Kg5 Kf7 35. b5 b6 36. h3 $22 {If king goes to queen
side, then h7 is lost; and if it goes to the king side, then the White king
goes to the queen side.} Kg7 37. Kf5 Kf7 38. Ke5 Ke7 39. Kd5 Kd7 40. h4 h5 41.
Ke5 $18 {And the h5 pawn is lost.}) 34. a5 Kg8 35. b5 Kh8 36. c5 c6 37. bxc6
bxc6 38. Kg5 Kg7 39. Kf5 Kf7 40. Ke5 Ke7 41. h3 {The battle in such structures
of opening is whether White can successfully stop Black from playing both f5
and e5. If he can, then he will get a good position; but if Black can make e5
and f5 possible, then White will be worse - as could have happened in the game.
} 1-0

