1. c4 Nf6 2. Nc3 e6 3. e4 d5 4. e5 d4 5. exf6 dxc3 6. bxc3 Qxf6 7. Nf3 {With
this move, White signals his hypermodern strategy. He does not want to capture
the centre with d4, instead first developing the bishop on d3 and - only after
Bc2 - playing d4.} e5 8. Bd3 Bg4 $1 {A very logical move, adhering to the
principle of maximum activity. It's true that by the principle of least active
piece, we must develop our knights before the bishop, but in this particular
case we are still not sure whether we want the knight to be developed on d7 or
c6, and hence we first develop our light-squared bishop. We are now
threatening to take on f3 and ruin White's pawn structure.} 9. Be4 $1 {The
bishop turns out to be very strong on this square. It not only defends the f3
knight and prevents White's structure from being spoilt, but it also attack
the Black queen side which has been weakened due to the early development of
the bishop on g4.} Nd7 $1 {Fantastic concept introduced by Naiditsch!! He
develops his least active piece to a square from where it can eye the weakened
c5 square and attack the e4 bishop. Thus, in a way, this move is aimed at
neutralising the activity of the e4 bishop at the earliest possible
opportunity. The cost of this is the b7 pawn, but Black is ready to pay that
price.} (9... c6 {Would look like the most natural move, blunting the bishop;
but it runs into the very annoying move...} 10. d4 $1 $16 {When White is
clearly better, as he has superior development, more central space and good
pieces; besides the open 'b' file can be used to put pressure on the b7 pawn.}
exd4 11. O-O dxc3 12. Re1 Be7 13. Qb3 $36) 10. Bxb7 {The only test of
Naiditsch's idea.} (10. d4 {Is no longer so strong.} exd4 $1 11. O-O (11. cxd4
$6 Bb4+ $1) 11... dxc3 12. Bxb7 Rb8 13. Re1+ Be7 $15 {Black is doing very well.
}) 10... Rb8 11. Bd5 (11. Rb1 {Is not so good because of the precise move...}
c6 $1 12. Qa4 Be7 13. Rb3 O-O {Threatening Nc5.} 14. d4 Bxf3 15. gxf3 exd4 16.
cxd4 Qxd4 $17 {Black is just better in this position, as he is ahead in
development and has a safer king.}) (11. Be4 {Doesn't change much, as the pawn
would be on c7 instead of on c6 as in the game.}) 11... c6 12. Be4 Nc5 {At the
cost of a pawn, Black has tremendous activity. He is attacking the very strong
bishop on e4 and, at the same time, his rook stands very well on the open 'b'
file.} 13. Qe2 (13. h3 Bh5 (13... Nxe4 14. hxg4 $16) 14. Qe2 Nxe4 15. Qxe4 Bxf3
16. Qxf3 Qxf3 17. gxf3 {Would lead us to the same position in the game, just
that the pawn on is on h3 instead of h2. Maybe it's a fact that ever so
slightly favours White, as his pawn is now not on the square of his bishop.})
13... Nxe4 14. Qxe4 Bxf3 15. Qxf3 Qxf3 16. gxf3 {After some exchanges, we
reach a position that is extremely imbalanced. White has an extra pawn. In
return, Black has a better pawn structure and open file for his b8 rook.
White's extra pawn doesn't really count right now, as it will take a long time
to realise its strength; meanwhile, Black must try to take up as many active
posts as possible for his four pieces. (Yes in the endgame, the king is also
an important piece).} Kd7 {In the endgame, even the king is a fighting unit.}
17. Ke2 Bd6 {In a way, taking aim at the h2 pawn and clearing the way for the
rook to come to e8.} 18. Rd1 Rhe8 $1 {Now d4 becomes difficult to execute and
the e8 rook can lift itself to the third rank and start attacking the 'h' pawn.
All in all, I have a feeling that Black is enjoying playing this position much
more than White.} 19. d3 f5 $1 {Central expansion.} 20. h3 f4 $1 {You might
ask now - what is Black doing? Isn't placing all the pawns on the same colour
as your bishop a bad idea? Yes, it is a bad idea - but in this position it is
also restricting the c1 bishop and, in a way, has isolated the h3 pawn which
will now be attacked by the rook.} 21. Kf1 {Preparing d4.} g5 22. d4 exd4 {
Black doesn't mind straightening White's pawn structure, as he now gets fresh
targets to attack.} 23. cxd4 Rb4 $1 {Active play - again, forcing White to
push his 'c' pawn and thus fixing the pawns on dark squares.} 24. c5 Bf8 {
Planning to reroute the bishop to g7, where it will attack the d4 pawn.} 25.
Ba3 (25. d5 Bxc5 $15) 25... Ra4 26. Rd3 Bg7 27. Rb1 Ke6 28. Rb7 Rxd4 29. Rdb3
$2 (29. Rxd4 Bxd4 30. Rxh7 Kd5 31. Rh5 Re5 $11 {Was a better way for White to
play.}) 29... Rd1+ $1 30. Ke2 Red8 $1 $17 {I think this is the move Movsesian
missed. Due to the mate on d2, he cannot take the g7 bishop. Black has won
back the pawn and kept all his positional trumps. In short, he is just better.}
31. Bb4 R8d7 32. Bc3 Bf8 33. R7b4 Bxc5 34. Rc4 R1d5 35. Rb8 Kf5 36. Re8 Bd4 37.
Rf8+ Ke5 38. Re8+ Kf5 39. Rf8+ Ke5 40. Rxc6 Bxc3 41. Re8+ Kf5 42. Rf8+ Ke5 43.
Re8+ Kf5 44. Rf8+ 1/2-1/2

