1. c4 Nf6 2. Nc3 e6 3. e4 (3. d4 Bb4 {Will transpose into the Nimzo Indian
opening.}) 3... d5 4. e5 d4 5. exf6 dxc3 6. bxc3 Qxf6 7. d4 e5 8. Nf3 Nc6 $1 {
I like this move, over the more popular move ed4. Here is some brief analysis
why I don't really prefer ed4. You can skip these comments, but going over
them will give you an idea as to what exact problems Black is facing.} (8...
exd4 {I analysed this move extensively and came to the conclusion that Black
has to play very accurately to hold the balance - something that is possible
for strong GMs but not for mere mortals! So I think 8...Nc6 is better.} 9. Bg5
$1 {This is the most critical move.} (9. cxd4 $6 {This obvious recapture helps
Black equalise with ease.} Bb4+ 10. Bd2 Bxd2+ 11. Qxd2 O-O 12. Be2 Re8 13. O-O
Bg4 14. Rfe1 Nc6 {(Black completes his normal development and achieves an
equal position.)} 15. d5 Rad8 $11) 9... Qe6+ {Gaining a tempo to develop his
pieces. This game will now shift to a phase where Black's static advantages
will fight against White's dynamic ones.} 10. Be2 Be7 $5 {This seems to be the
most solid move in the position for Black.} (10... d3 $2 {Doesn't work due to..
.} 11. O-O $1 {The fact that the Black king and queen are on the same file
will induce a tactical refutation.} Qxe2 $2 (11... dxe2 $2 12. Qd8#) 12. Re1
$18) (10... f6 {Is also one of the main moves in this position, but it doesn't
develop pieces and weakens the king side. I don't like it very much.} 11. Nxd4
$36 {With a strong initiative for White.}) 11. cxd4 (11. Bxe7 $5 {Now Black
has a very interesting intermediate move...} d3 $5 {This move is very
important, as Black wants White's pawns to remain weak on c3 and c4.} 12. O-O (
12. Qxd3) 12... Qxe7 (12... Qxe2 $2 {This is just a mistake due to...} 13. Qb3
$1 Qxe7 (13... Kxe7 14. Rfe1 $18) 14. Rfe1 Be6 15. Qxb7 $16 {And White has a
winning position.}) 13. Bxd3 O-O $1 {Safeguarding the king. Let's have a look
at this position and talk about it. Material is even, but White's pawns are
horrible. It might seem he is just worse - but that will be a static point of
view. What is more important to note is that White is extremely well developed
and has the better pieces. If Black can quench White's activity, then he can
be better - but as of now his work is cut out to play carefully.} 14. Qc2 (14.
Re1 Qf6 15. Be4) 14... g6 {With the idea of Na6-c5.} 15. Rae1 Qf6 {It's a
fight between White's activity and Blacks long-term advantages.}) (11. O-O $6
Bxg5 12. Nxg5 Qe7 13. Qc1 h6 14. Nf3 dxc3 15. Qxc3 O-O $15 {White doesn't have
any compensation for his lost pawn.}) 11... Bxg5 12. Nxg5 Qg6 {Is the latest
try.} 13. f4 O-O 14. O-O Nc6 15. d5 Ne7 {White is slightly better, but Black
can equalise if he makes good accurate moves. This is a position that is not
so much fun for Black to play.}) 9. dxe5 $6 {This move is a bad mistake. Of
course, positionally you can clearly see that this move leaves the 'c' pawns
horribly weak, as they are doubled and isolated, But White is trying to take
advantage of short-term tactics, namely the pin down the 'e' file. The problem
is that Black wriggles out of it and all that White is left is with manifold
weaknesses.} Nxe5 $1 {Rising up to the challenge is what you can expect from a
talented youngster like So Wesley.} 10. Qe2 {The only move that justifies
White's prior play.} Bd6 $1 11. Bg5 (11. c5 {Might have been the reason why
White played this way, but he must have realised a little too late that Black
can now win the game with...} O-O $1 {Black continues to develop his pieces,
